Line 1. 512 ciphertext
Line 2. 256 keys
Line 3. 512 presence & absence indicators (Tells which ciphertext to decrypt and which to ignore).
Line 4. Their message                     (Authenticated; a SHA-512 hash of the last 3 lines is actually what's represented by key presence & absence).
Line 5. Their new number                  (Authenticated; a SHA-512 hash of the last 3 lines is actually what's represented by key presence & absence).
Line 6. Approximately 15 zeros



Zeros in line 6 make the last 3
lines produce a SHA-512 hash
with 256 0 bits and 256 1 bits.

Hence strictly 256 keys are used.
Otherwise if you could use arbitrarily
many keys, attackers could interject the
publishing of your public file and withhold
whichever keys allows "presence and absence"
to represent their strings and not your own.
